2.2.3 Basic map making

plot(world[3:6])

plot(world["pop"])

You can overlay using add = TRUE

world_asia = world[world$continent == "Asia", ]
asia = st_union(world_asia)
plot(world["pop"], reset = FALSE)
plot(asia, add = TRUE, col = "red")

plot(world["continent"], reset = FALSE)
cex = sqrt(world$pop) / 10000
world_cents = st_centroid(world, of_largest = TRUE)
st_centroid assumes attributes are constant over geometries of xst_centroid does not give correct centroids for longitude/latitude data
plot(st_geometry(world_cents), add = TRUE, cex = cex)

india = world[world$name_long == "India", ]
plot(st_geometry(india), expandBB = c(0, 0.2, 0.1, 1), col = "gray", lwd = 3)
plot(world_asia[0], add = TRUE)

18 Levels: GEOMETRY POINT LINESTRING POLYGON MULTIPOINT MULTILINESTRING MULTIPOLYGON GEOMETRYCOLLECTION ... TRIANGLE
## POLYGON with a hole
polygon_border = rbind(c(1, 5), c(2, 2), c(4, 1), c(4, 4), c(1, 5))
polygon_hole = rbind(c(2, 4), c(3, 4), c(3, 3), c(2, 3), c(2, 4))
polygon_with_hole_list = list(polygon_border, polygon_hole)
polygon_with_hole = st_polygon(polygon_with_hole_list)
plot(polygon_with_hole)

It is also possible to create an sfc object from sfg objects with different geometry types:

All geometries in an sfc object must have the same CRS.

st_crs(points_sfc_wgs)

Coordinate Reference System:
  EPSG: 4326 
  proj4string: "+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs"
st_crs(world)

  EPSG: 4326 
  proj4string: "+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs"

2.4.3 CRSs in R

new_vector = st_set_crs(new_vector, 4326) # set CRS

st_crs<- : replacing crs does not reproject data; use st_transform for that
plot(new_vector)

plotting the first 9 out of 11 attributes; use max.plot = 11 to plot allbounding box has potentially an invalid value range for longlat data
